abstract: How an ambitious kid from Leeds, England, became one of the most powerful media people in New York.
snippet: How an ambitious kid from Leeds, England, became one of the most powerful media people in New York.
lead_paragraph: In the back of a cab heading up Central Park West, Joanna Coles, the editor of Cosmopolitan, was telling the story of her first meeting in Rome with the designer Valentino Garavani.

abstract: It’s the kind of choice that climate change will be forcing over and over.
snippet: It’s the kind of choice that climate change will be forcing over and over.
lead_paragraph: It was a few minutes before noon on Tangier Island in Virginia, just about high tide, when David Schulte pushed the toe of his red sneaker into Marilyn Pruitt’s soggy backyard. Schulte, a marine biologist with the United States Army Corps of Engineers, frowned, withdrew his foot, found another spot nearby and pressed his toe down again. His sneaker sank into the ground, and water pooled around it. “It’s like that all the time,” Pruitt called out from her back porch. “It doesn’t dry out anymore.”

abstract: Nearly 6 percent of all third through eighth graders must attend the classes, down from 6.3 percent last year, the city’s Education Department said.
snippet: Nearly 6 percent of all third through eighth graders must attend the classes, down from 6.3 percent last year, the city’s Education Department said.
lead_paragraph: Fewer students will be required to go to summer school this year, the New York City Education Department said on Thursday, continuing a downward trend under Mayor Bill de Blasio.
headline_main: Fewer New York Students Will Attend Summer School, Continuing a Trend
headline_print_headline: Fewer Students Will Attend Summer School This Year

abstract: Sunset yoga in the Bronx, a reading of the Declaration of Independence in Mount Vernon, and Afro Latin jazz in Woodstock are just a few of the events that are lined up for the coming days.

headline_main: Things to Do in the Hudson Valley, July 2 Through July 10

abstract: A world-class walking city has turned into an obstacle course, and transportation officials are moving to ease the congestion.
snippet: A world-class walking city has turned into an obstacle course, and transportation officials are moving to ease the congestion.
lead_paragraph: Ivette Singh hardly bothers to walk on the sidewalk on her way to work in Midtown Manhattan anymore. Too many people, too little space. Not enough patience.

lead_paragraph: PUERTO RICO RELIEF MEASURE CLEARS SENATE The Senate passed and sent to the White House a relief measure to help Puerto Rico surmount its fiscal crisis, just two days before the territory planned to default on a large debt payment, Jackie Calmes reports in The New York Times. President Obama will sign the measure, which his Treasury secretary, Jacob J. Lew, negotiated and lobbied for.

abstract: If an agreement is reached, it would be the end of a long road for Starz, which has been the subject of merger speculation for three years.
snippet: If an agreement is reached, it would be the end of a long road for Starz, which has been the subject of merger speculation for three years.
lead_paragraph: Lionsgate is near a deal to buy Starz, uniting the film studio behind “The Hunger Games” with the premium cable home of the “Outlander” television series, a person briefed on the matter said on Wednesday.

abstract: The long-stalled performing arts center, which will sit on an emotionally resonant and highly visited spot in the city, will be named for Mr. Perelman.
snippet: The long-stalled performing arts center, which will sit on an emotionally resonant and highly visited spot in the city, will be named for Mr. Perelman.
lead_paragraph: Less than a year since he stepped down as the chairman of Carnegie Hall after clashing with its staff, Ronald O. Perelman, the billionaire businessman, announced Wednesday that he was donating $75 million to revive plans to build a performing arts center at the World Trade Center site.
